<h3 id="resolutions-add-or-subtract">Resolutions: add, or subtract?</h3>
<p>Personally, I donâ€™t do New Yearâ€™s resolutions. I prefer to check in every month (usually on Sundays) on how the things Iâ€™m doing are furthering my main values, or <a href="https://www.carlpullein.com/podcast/why-everything-must-start-from-your-areas-of-focus/14/9/2020" target="_blank">areas of focus</a>. See <a href="https://ellanew.com/2024/09/16/ptpl-122-value-driven-tasks" title="wikilink">2024-09-16 <span class="small-caps">PTPL</span> 122 - Aligning Your Task List with Your (Changing) Values</a></p>
<p>Mike Schmitz said recently <a href="https://practicalpkm.com/the-ultimate-productivity-hack/" target="_blank">the ultimate productivity hack</a> is to subtract things from your life, not add them. In my experience adding is usually better than subtracting, but it can require a mindset shift.</p>
<p>Focus your mind on adding the good thing you want to achieve (stronger muscles, a sense of peace and order at home, more time with family), have an attitude of working towards that, and youâ€™ll come to see how to drop or adopt the practices needed to get you there. If your psyche resists losing things, you can work with, not against, that.</p>
