<p>To finish, here are some links to past <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl" title="wikilink"><span class="small-caps">PTPL</span></a> posts you may find helpful.</p>
<p><em><a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/062-human-joy-more-important-than-productivity" title="wikilink"><span class="small-caps">PTPL</span> 062</a> - An invitation to review your personal areas of focus, and create a personal manifesto.</em> Do you know what your productivity efforts are costing you? Take a moment to observe the time and attention you put into your work or solo hobbies, and consider how well it balances with what are ultimately your highest priorities. Keep in mind that human joy (your own, and that which you share with others) will always be more important than raw productivity.</p>
<p>Remember, <strong>you can do (almost) anything, but you canâ€™t do everything: not today, this week, or this life</strong>. Add one or two things to tomorrowâ€™s to do list that will further a core area or value. Do this most days and results will come!</p>
<p><em><a href="https://ellanew.com/2023/05/22/ptpl-053-plain-text-vehicle-productivity-destination" title="wikilink"><span class="small-caps">PTPL</span> 053</a> - Digital independence is good, but itâ€™s not all there is.</em> How tragic would it be if I devoted my entire life to building a finely-crafted system that reaches admirable pinnacles of future-proof, plain text app-agnosticism, only to realise at the end Iâ€™d neglected to actually <em>do</em> something worthwhile with my notes? The means are important but theyâ€™re the vehicle, not the destination.</p>
